-- China Shenhua, Kweichow Moutai, Huaneng, Beiqi Foton: China Equity Preview
-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 2010-12-16T00:29:08Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-16/china-shenhua-kweichow-moutai-huaneng-beiqi-foton-china-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
 unusual  price changes in China trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and share prices are as of yesterday’s close.  The  Shanghai Composite Index , which tracks the bigger of
China’s stock exchanges, retreated 0.5 percent to 2,911.41. The
 CSI 300 Index  lost 0.7 percent to 3,247.64.  Banks: The China Banking Regulatory Commission’s Shanghai
branch ordered halts on lending to companies for purchases of
fixed assets until the end of the year, the Oriental Morning
Post reported, citing unidentified people familiar with the
matter.  Industrial and Commercial Bank of China Ltd.  (601398 CH),
the nation’s largest lender, slid 1.2 percent to 4.22 yuan.  Bank
of China Ltd.  (601988 CH) declined 0.6 percent.  Home-appliance makers: China will continue offering
subsidies to rural home-appliance buyers next year, Xinhua News
Agency reported, citing contracts the government signed with
manufacturers yesterday. The program covers 15,290 models of
televisions, refrigerators, washing machines, microwave ovens,
air conditioners, computers and water heaters, Xinhua said.  Qingdao Haier Co.  (600690 CH) dropped 0.8 percent to 26.91
yuan. TCL Corp. (000100 CH), China’s biggest television maker,
slid 0.6 percent to 3.56 yuan.  Sichuan Changhong Electric Co. 
(600839 CH) added 0.3 percent to 3.95 yuan.  Yanzhou Coal Mining Co.  (600188 CH): Central China’s
thermal coal stockpiles dropped to 13.5 million metric tons, or
enough for 15 days of use, Xinhua News Agency reported after the
market closed yesterday, citing the country’s power grid company.
Coal stockpiles fell on rising winter demand for electricity,
according to the report. The listed unit of China’s fourth-
biggest coal miner rose 1.8 percent to 29.75 yuan.  China Shenhua Energy Co.  (601088 CH): The nation’s largest
coal producer said it won approval from the National Development
and Reform Commission to build a coal rail link in northern
China at a cost of 13.5 billion yuan ($2 billion), and will
expand the Huanghua coal port. The stock added 1.3 percent to
25.19 yuan.  Beijing Capital Development Co.  (600376 CH): The property
developer said will invest 300 million yuan for a 49 percent
stake in a real estate joint venture in Shenyang city. The
shares declined 1.3 percent to 15.35 yuan.  Beiqi Foton Motor Co.  (600166 CH): China’s biggest
commercial-vehicle maker said its November sales rose to 56,816
units from 53,873 units a year earlier. The stock fell 1 percent
to 25.51 yuan.  Huaneng Power International Inc.  (600011 CH): The listed
unit of China’s largest power group said a power project at its
Qinbei plant, which is estimated to cost 4.18 billion yuan, won
approval from the National Development and Reform Commission.
The shares declined 0.5 percent to 6.17 yuan.  Kweichow Moutai Co.  (600519 CH): China’s biggest liquor
maker by market value will increase prices by 20 percent on
average starting Jan. 1, citing higher production costs. The
stock gained 1.4 percent to 200.70 yuan.  Zhengzhou Yutong Bus Co.  (600066 CH): The bus maker plans
to invest 45 million yuan ($6.75 million) for a 15 percent stake
in a finance venture with its parent. The shares dropped 1.4
percent to 22.73 yuan.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at 
 dboey@bloomberg.net  